{
  "explanation": "The defendant is a first-time offender who committed a non-violent financial crime of $25,000 and has already begun restitution. While embezzlement is a serious breach of trust, the sentencing guidelines for a non-violent, first-time white-collar offense of this magnitude generally favor a rehabilitative approach, often including probation, restitution, and a short period of incarceration to serve as a deterrent. The spectator's outburst is irrelevant to the legal merits of the case and has been disregarded in determining the sentence. A term of 6 months serves as a sufficient punitive measure for the breach of fiduciary duty while acknowledging the defendant's lack of prior criminal history and proactive effort to repay the stolen funds.",
  "verdict": 6
}
